Fireblight - Australia (02) 19970724.1557
Fireblight - Australia: RFI 19970723.1543
Date: 17 Oct 2000
From: Dick Hamilton rihamilto@home.com
Source: The Age, 12 Oct 2000 [edited
<http://www.theage.com.au/news/20001012/A45193-2000Oct11.html>

Australian farmers fear apple blight
------------------------------------
Australian apple and pear growers fear their $400 million industry could be
destroyed by fire blight following a [recent recommendation by the Federal
Government's quarantine authority to overturn a ban on apple imports from
New Zealand. A draft risk assessment released by Biosecurity Australia set
out conditions for New Zealand apples to enter Australia provided they pass
stringent tests. New Zealand, plagued by fire blight for decades, has been
putting enormous political pressure on Australia to remove its ban on apple
imports, reimposed in 1998.
Australian Apple and Pear Growers Association chief executive Jon Durham
[said that the industry would be contacting international experts on plant
diseases to [assist the association to respond to the assessment within 60
days. Durham [believes that safeguards outlined in the statement [would
not protect Australia's orchards from the crippling disease, [warning that
the disease [could destroy Australia's pear industry and severely impact on
most modern apple orchards.
Australia is one of only a few fruit-growing countries not affected by fire
blight. The [bacterium disfigures and kills fruit trees and the only
chemical known to have any effect on [the pathogen is not allowed in
Australia. Victoria's Goulburn Valley region, which produces apples and
pears worth about $200 million annually, is especially vulnerable because of
climatic factors and the use of susceptible cultivars.
The Federal Government is expected to come under pressure from the states to
maintain the ban on New Zealand apples.
[Byline: Richard Baker
